"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101233","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The latest information published by The Pensions Regulator shows that over 4.7 million eligible jobholders have been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension. It is not possible to identify how many of these jobholders had no prior pension savings.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-11-03T15:37:32.6780562Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101233/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101233/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who had no prior pension savings have been enrolled under automatic enrolment into workplace pension schemes.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Hoban","Fareham","Mr Mark Hoban","212139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101234","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>This data was not historically recorded and we are therefore unable to provide the information that you have requested. The Access to Work reconsideration process has now changed but guidance is yet to be updated. We no longer have 5 stages of reconsideration.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T17:41:27.7792078Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101234/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101234/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people whose primary medical condition was classified as difficulty in hearing sought reconsideration of their case from (a) a regional Access to Work manager, (b) a senior operational manager, (c) a national AtW delivery manager, (d) a customer services director responsible for AtW and (e) an independent case examiner in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","212121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101235","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Findings from qualitative research with large employers show the overall opt out rate was around 9 per cent. Most individual employers had an opt out rate between 5 and 15 per cent. Opt out is only possible within the opt out window which is one month after being automatically enrolled.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-11-03T15:39:46.6832615Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101235/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101235/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of people enrolled under automatic workplace pension schemes have chosen to opt out after (a) six, (b) nine and (c) 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Hoban","Fareham","Mr Mark Hoban","212140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101236","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>Access to Work carries out reviews periodically for all customers, the frequency of these varies from case to case. This information is not recorded and we are therefore unable to provide the data that you have requested.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T17:44:03.9049185Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101236/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101236/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many users of the Access to Work scheme with each primary medical condition received reductions to their support package after a review of their support in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","212122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101237","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>Access to Work does not have an historic means of reporting on DWP programme participant volumes nor do we have a means of reporting DWP programme participant volumes for specific constituencies, or geographical districts. Cases are recorded by disability type, not by the categories specific to your request.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T17:48:56.977977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101237/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101237/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Access to Work Programme: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many disabled people in (a) Bury St Edmunds constituency and (b) Suffolk have received new support from the Access to Work scheme to participate in internships, traineeships and work placements since September 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","211955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101238","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>The information requested is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-11-03T13:09:03.1125982Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101238/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101238/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Unemployment Benefits: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have made at least one claim for out-of-work benefits in (a) Bury St. Edmunds constituency, (b) Suffolk and (c) the East of England since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","211956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101239","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p>Bury St Edmunds Jobcentre and all Suffolk Jobcentres provide public computers with internet access for jobseekers to use. Staff are available to offer individual coaching and to support jobseekers completing online applications.</p><p> </p><p>Several partner organisations including New Careers Service and F1 Training support jobseekers through online job applications and up skill them to be self-sufficient in online recruitment processes. FiftyON East and TCHC also offer this support specifically for older jobseekers.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-11-03T13:16:29.8288564Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101239/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101239/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Employment Services: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps are being taken in (a) Bury St Edmunds constituency and (b) Suffolk to support older jobseekers in using online recruitment processes.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","211957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101240","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-04","<p>Higher education institutions are autonomous and independent bodies. They are responsible for meeting their legal obligation to promote disability equality and make reasonable adjustments for disabled people under the Disability Act 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s funding reforms are providing significant and rising income to institutions to perform all of their duties, including those relating to disability.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","212025","2014-11-04T11:22:04.4947471Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101240/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101240/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-27","Higher Education: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the funding that higher education institutions receive to recruit and support disabled students is ring-fenced for that purpose.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","212002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101241","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T17:46:23.5056833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101241/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101241/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Disability Living Allowance: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the (a) maximum and (b) average length of time was for processing a new claim for disability living allowance for children in (i) 2009 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","211950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101242","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>Access to Work does not have a means of reporting DWP programme volumes for specific constituencies, or geographical districts. Cases are recorded by disability type, not by the categories specific to your request.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T17:41:34.7433649Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101242/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101242/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Access to Work Programme: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many disabled people are using Access to Work support for a (a) work trial, (b) work experience opportunity under the Youth Contract, (c) supported internship, (d) traineeship and (e) pre-employment training work placement in (i) Bury St Edmunds constituency, (ii) Suffolk and (iii) the East of England.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","211954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101243","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p>The Government considers a disregard of occupational/personal pension income of £85.00 a week before contributory Employment and Support Allowance is reduced to be reasonable. This is being currently reviewed as part of the annual benefits uprating exercise.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","212050","2014-11-03T17:51:27.7997098Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101243/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101243/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the level of income disregard threshold for employment and support allowance will be reviewed prior to the Autumn Statement 2014.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","212041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101244","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-30","<p>The information requested for work capability assessments by parliamentary constituency is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of registrations and clearances of claims to personal independence payment (PIP) has been published and is available on the GOV.UK website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-july-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-july-2014</a>. There are several stages between registration and clearance of a PIP claim including: the issue and return of the PIP questionnaire; an assessment by a health professional, usually at a face-to-face consultation; and a decision on the claim by a DWP decision maker.</p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-30T14:21:15.1025952Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101244/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101244/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people were waiting in each parliamentary constituency for (a) a work capability assessment and (b) a decision for a personal independence payment claim on the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","212031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101245","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions provided funding to disabled people in (a) Scotland of £6M and (b) GB £108M through the Access to Work scheme in 2013-14.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-30T12:49:01.2723028Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101245/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101245/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what funding was provided to disabled people in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK through the Access to Work scheme in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","211995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101246","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-30","<p /> <p>35,530 individuals were helped through Access to Work in GB in the 2013/14 financial year. 2,830 of which were in Scotland.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-30T13:59:50.5783008Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101246/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101246/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK received support through the Access to Work scheme in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","211996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101247","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p>The Government considers a disregard of occupational/personal pension income of £85.00 a week before contributory Employment and Support Allowance is reduced to be reasonable. This is being currently reviewed as part of the annual benefits uprating exercise.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","212041","2014-11-03T17:51:28.0658759Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101247/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101247/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2014 to question 201294, for what reason it was decided not to change the income disregard threshold for employment and support allowance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","212050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101248","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>A Case Manager, the term for a DWP DLA decision maker, will conduct the review. In conducting the review, DLA Case Managers are instructed, through training and guidance, to ensure they have all the necessary information before making their decision. They will consider the evidence held and/or received, sending out for more evidence as appropriate, and only then make their decision.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T17:47:22.4547717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101248/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101248/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-27","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, who the decision maker is in the case of a DLA review; and what the assessment process is.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","212004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101547","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-30","<p>We are spending more than £3.2 billion over period of this parliament, compared to £2.7 billion in the previous five years. By March 2015, we will have improved the level of protection to more than 165,000 households.</p><p>We have also improved the funding approach to encourage others to invest in flood defences, so even more schemes can be delivered.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-30T17:49:17.1932667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101547/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101547/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-27","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent steps she has taken to promote flood defences.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","905750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101548","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-30","<p>Stormwater drainage is a matter for local authorities in their capacity as lead local flood authorities, and it is their responsibility to make an assessment of the risk. Local authorities are accountable to local people for the adequacy of the drainage infrastructure in their areas.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-30T17:43:42.5787987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101548/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101548/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-27","Sewers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment she has made of the adequacy of stormwater drainage in residential areas.","false","Biography information for Duncan Hames","Chippenham","Duncan Hames","905747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101602","Public Accounts Commission","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Commission, working with the National Audit Office, has taken significant steps to reduce expenditure by the NAO. By the 31st March 2015, NAO expenditure will have reduced by 20% from its 2010–11 baseline of £74.1 million. This is a cut of more than 25% after adjusting for inflation.</p><p>The Commission will be discussing future resource proposals for the National Audit Office at a hearing scheduled for 2nd December 2014. This discussion will also consider the additional responsibilities in local government the NAO will take on following the passage of the Local Audit and Accountability Act 2014.</p>","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh",,"2014-10-30T10:27:11.2985015Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101602/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101602/answer",,,,,"24","Public Accounts Commission","Public Accounts Commission","2014-10-27","National Audit Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chairman of the Public Accounts Commission, if the Commission will take steps to reduce expenditure by the National Audit Office.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Turner","Isle of Wight","Mr Andrew Turner","905730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101703","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-30","<p>Food and farming is a vital part of our economy, generating £100bn and employing one in eight people. We want to enable farmers to spend their time producing high quality British produce and contribute to this. This is why, by the end of this Parliament, we will have reduced the volume of guidance by 80%.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-30T16:07:02.9060885Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101703/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101703/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-27","Agriculture: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress she is making in reducing the burden of regulation on farmers.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","905755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101704","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-30","<p>There are currently 70 British food and drink products with protected status.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-30T18:15:52.6891753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101704/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101704/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-27","Food: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many British food and drink products have protected status.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","905757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101705","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-30","<p>Biodiversity policy is a devolved matter. In England, our Biodiversity 202 strategy includes a wide range of policies aimed at protecting, restoring and creating wildlife habitats, and halting the decline in plant and animal species. Central to delivering this ambition are our agri-environment schemes, which help farmers to manage their land in an environmentally friendly way. Over £3.1 billion will be spent on environmental objectives under our schemes between 2014 and 2020.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-30T18:16:23.2075172Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101705/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101705/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-27","Nature Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to protect plants and wildlife in the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Mosley","City of Chester","Stephen Mosley","905753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101706","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-30","<p>The proposals for flood defence improvement projects on the Humber Estuary are being considered as part of the six-year capital investment programme, which will be published with the Autumn Statement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency is also reviewing the Humber Flood Risk Management Strategy, which will consider future investment needs across the estuary. It will take account of data gathered following the east coast tidal surge of December 2013.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-10-30T17:44:43.3261007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101706/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101706/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-27","Flood Control: Humber Estuary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the merits of recent proposals to strengthen flood defences in the Humber Estuary.","false","Biography information for Martin Vickers","Cleethorpes","Martin Vickers","905754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100841","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-11","<p>UK Trade and Investment (UKTI) works in line with the Government’s Industrial Strategy. The whole UKTI network works predominantly in these priority sectors to support UK exporters and attract foreign direct investment to the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of civil service staff working in our core sector teams in our HQ, and the budget allocated to each team[1].</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Staff</p></td><td><p>Budget, £m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Advanced Manufacturing</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>1.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UKTI Agri-Tech Organisation</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>1.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UKTI Automotive Investment Organisation</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Construction</p></td><td><p>10.5</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Consumer &amp; Retail</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>2.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Creative Industries &amp; Global Sports</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>2.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UKTI Education</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>1.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Energy</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>2.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UKTI Financial Services Organisation</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>2.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Healthcare UK</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>1.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Information Economy</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>3.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Innovation Gateway</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UKTI Life Science Organisation</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>2.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UKTI Offshore Wind Investment Organisation</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UKTI DSO</p></td><td><p>128</p></td><td><p>10.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] This core resource is supplemented by specialist contractors, sector teams in our global network, and our trade advisors in the English regions. The core budget is supplemented by funding for cross-cutting activity including trade fairs and missions, marketing, and the services provided by our 430 Trade Advisors in the English regions to help UK companies export to new markets.</p><p>It should be noted that UKTI DSO operates as a separate unit, whereas the other UKTI sector teams utilise more shared resource in addition to the numbers tabled below.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-11T15:17:07.428811Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100841/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100841/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-24","UK Trade and Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many UK Trade and Investment staff worked in each of the industrial sectors on 1 April 2014; and what the budget for each such sector is in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","211850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100842","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-03","<p>At 1 April 2014 the UK Trade and Investment Defence and Security Organisation had 128 staff-in-post. As at 1 April the 2014-15 budget for UKTI DSO was £10.5M NET.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-03T12:48:31.2071345Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100842/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100842/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-24","UKTI Defence and Security Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff worked for the UK Trade and Investment Defence and Security Organisation (UKTI DSO) on 1 April 2014; and what the budget of the UKTI DSO is for 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","211851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100843","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-03","<p>The Government has not undertaken a formal assessment of the merits of pro-active investigations but believes they are an important part of enforcement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC published findings from their targeted social care evaluation on 25 November 2013. Over the period 1 April 2011 to 31 March 2013, HMRC had made enquiries into 224 employers in the social care sector. Of the cases completed by the end of September 2014, HMRC have found non-compliance in 108 (48%) of their enquiries, identifying £1,319,729 arrears of pay for 6,550 workers, with penalties issued with a total value of £146,931.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of this targeted enforcement activity, HMRC have collaborated with care sector representative bodies to improve understanding of compliance risks and design controls within payroll systems that prevent workers being underpaid the minimum wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department of Health has recently published statutory guidance for local authorities as part of the package of secondary legislation that accompanies the Care Act. The chapter of statutory guidance on commissioning and market shaping explicitly states that local authorities should have evidence that contract terms, conditions and fee levels will not compromise care providers’ ability to pay at least minimum wages. A copy of the guidance can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/care-act-2014-statutory-guidance-for-implementation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/care-act-2014-statutory-guidance-for-implementation</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department of Health is asking all Local Authorities to sign up to the Social Care Commitment which incorporates a statement about employer compliance with minimum wage legislation. The Association of Directors of Adult Social Services has written out to all its members encouraging them to support the Commitment as a way of raising standards in adult social care.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We regularly update our Guidance on Gov.UK and we will continue to work with the sector to improve understanding and compliance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any worker who believes that they are being paid below the minimum wage should call the Pay &amp; Work Rights Helpline on 0800 917 2368. HM Revenue &amp; Customs investigate all complaints.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-03T11:47:07.1944946Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100843/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100843/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-24","Social Services: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the merits of HM Revenue and Customs launching pro-active investigations into the non-payment of the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","211865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100844","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-03","<p>The cost of paying a one-off payment to the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills staff in lieu of their entitlement to annual increments was £3.2m. This cost is offset against a reduction in overall pay bill costs over the longer term.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The non-consolidated payments were staggered by grade in line with contractual step values.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>AA</p></td><td><p>£1008</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>AO</p></td><td><p>£1168</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>EO</p></td><td><p>£1360</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HEO</p></td><td><p>£1656</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SEO</p></td><td><p>£1880</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>G7</p></td><td><p>£2528</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>G6</p></td><td><p>£3060</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-03T12:46:36.980132Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100844/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100844/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-24","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the cost of paying a one-off payment to the staff of his Department in lieu of their entitlement to annual increments was.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","211898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100845","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>The seventh round of negotiations for the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) took place between 29 September and 3 October in Chevy Chase, Maryland. As expected, negotiations were largely focused on regulatory issues. Discussions also covered energy, intellectual property, small and medium sized enterprises (SMEs) and services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There was good technical progress, particularly on regulatory coherence, for example in the automotive and pharmaceutical sectors. This progress is crucial and prepares the ground for an ambitious and comprehensive agreement.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-06T13:58:22.816165Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100845/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100845/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-24","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what progress he has made on the recent round of discussions on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","211894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100846","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-03","<p>The payback period in relation to the one-off payment to the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills staff who opted to forego their entitlement to annual increment payment was estimated to be 6 years. This is based upon an assumption of 1% paybill increases year on year until 2020.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-03T11:40:24.6212023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100846/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100846/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-24","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the payback period is in relation to the one-off payment to staff in his Department who have opted to forego their entitlement to annual increment payments.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","211910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100847","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-04","<p>The Government encourages UK cities to take up innovative initiatives and adopt modern technology to respond to developing urban needs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has set up the Smart Cities Forum to bring together cities, industry and experts to identify and explore emerging policy issues. In order to benefit from the experiences of other Governments and European cities, the Government is a partner in a commitment within the European Innovation Partnership to share best practice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Future Cities Catapult has been established as a Centre of Excellence and works to develop and support urban innovation. Projects in Glasgow, London, Bristol and Peterborough have been funded by Innovate UK to demonstrate and display smart applications to improve city services and quality of life.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To ensure readiness to future developments, the Government Office for Science is undertaking the Foresight Future of Cities project, which explores opportunities and challenges facing UK cities over the next 50 years.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-11-04T16:38:44.7265638Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100847/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100847/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100847/answer/previousversion/25067","Biography information for Greg Clark","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-24","Technology: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what progress his Department has made with the Smart Cities programme; and if he will make a  statement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","211921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100848","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>Information on Verify is published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/introducing-govuk-verify" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/introducing-govuk-verify</a><br> <br>GOV.UK Verify provides the first opportunity for people to verify their identity entirely digitally. <br> The service has not yet been launched and is still in public beta. Performance data will be published in due course.</p><p>Government Digital Service has not received representations from public sector providers of identity assurance</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","211873 ; 211881","2014-10-29T17:49:36.8412924Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100848/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100848/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-24","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he has received representations on a public sector provider of identity assurance during the Gov.uk Verify programme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","211904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100849","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>Lord Wei was appointed to advise the Government on aspects of the Big Society. He held a Cabinet Office pass and had three officials assigned to work with him.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","211877","2014-10-29T16:59:22.7350838Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100849/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100849/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-24","Lord Wei","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether Lord Wei was an adviser to his Department; and whether he held a pass that allowed him to access the Cabinet Office.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","211880"
