"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100770","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p /> <p>Departmental statisticians are continuing to develop measures around clearance times and waiting times to ensure they provide a rounded and representative picture of personal independence payment performance, improvement activity and the claimants’ experience. These statistics will be published when they are ready, with the release pre-announced in line with United Kingdom Statistics Authority release protocols.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","211729","2014-10-28T14:04:45.4374656Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100770/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100770/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-23","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will include data on the average length of time taken to process personal independence payment claims in his Department's next quarterly statistics release.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","211677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100771","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p /> <p>It has always been the case that any UK national who has left the country for an extended period must satisfy the habitual residence test.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of concerns raised about the impact on returning UK nationals and are in the process of amending regulations to exempt from the three month residence requirement, members of the armed forces who have been posted abroad, Crown servants who have been posted abroad and others who had paid certain types of UK national insurance contributions during their absence abroad.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-28T16:57:36.45122Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100771/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100771/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-23","Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to waive the habitual residency test for jobseeker's allowance claimants when the claimant has lived abroad because of a parent being posted as a memember of the armed forces; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","211684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100772","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p>The latest official benefit cap statistics, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/benefit-cap-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/benefit-cap-statistics</a>, show that in East Ayrshire as at May 2014, there were 16 households subject to the cap.</p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-28T12:00:01.4751886Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100772/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100772/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-23","Housing Benefit: Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in East Ayrshire are currently subject to housing benefit being capped as a result of the benefit cap introduced in April 2013.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","211770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100773","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p>The latest official benefit cap statistics, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/benefit-cap-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/benefit-cap-statistics</a>, show that in East Ayrshire between April 2013 and May 2014, a total of 36 households have been capped.</p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-28T11:56:10.2541428Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100773/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100773/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-23","Housing Benefit: Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in East Ayrshire had had housing benefit capped since the introduction of the benefit cap at the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","211769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100774","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p /> <p>We will be publishing the Work Programme Building Best Practice Group report, and the department’s response to the recommendations made later on this autumn.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-28T11:28:06.835543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100774/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100774/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-23","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recommendations the Work Programme Building Best Practice Group has made to help the over 50s back to work.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","211781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100775","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-30","<p>The First-tier Tribunal (Social Security and Child Support), administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS), an Executive Agency of the Ministry of Justice, hears appeals against Department for Work and Pensions’ decisions on a range of benefits, including disability living allowance (DLA).</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of DLA appeals received by the Tribunal and the number found in favour of the appellant is published by Ministry of Justice in Tribunal Statistics Quarterly. Reports for DLA appeals dating back to 2010 can be viewed at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-30T16:26:14.4663074Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100775/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100775/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-23","Disability Living Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals against disability living allowance there have been since 2010; and how many such appeals resulted in a reversal of the original decision.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","211764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100776","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-30","<p>At present the Department does not hold any central data on the number of staff on personal improvement plans, as these are handled within the line management chain.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-30T14:59:54.6046995Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100776/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100776/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-23","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff in his Department (a) are currently on a personal improvement plan, (b) have been on a persoanl improvement plan for over one year and (c) have been on a personal improvement plan for more than two consecutive years; and what the grades are or were of such staff.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100777","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-30","<p>At present the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) does not hold any central data on the number of staff on personal improvement plans, as these are handled within the line management chain.</p><p>BIS currently has over 200 internal mentors; however, mentor relationships are confidential and therefore no data is held on how many of these are involved in mentoring staff on personal improvement plans.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-30T14:55:26.1312319Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100777/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100777/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-23","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff in his Department are responsible for mentoring staff on personal improvement plans.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100778","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-30","<p>At present the Department does not hold any central data on the number of staff on personal improvement plans, as these are handled within the line management chain.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-30T14:56:39.940765Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100778/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100778/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-23","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many teams in his Department currently have more than one member of staff on personal improvement plans.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100779","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) uses grading guidance as a tool to help managers and job holders determine the grading of a post. The guidance applies to all BIS staff, except the Senior Civil Service (SCS) and Fast Streamers, who have central grading structures.</p><p> </p><p>Job evaluation is used when the grading guidance alone is insufficient for the manager and job holder to determine the grade of a post. BIS uses a systematic job evaluation system called JEGS (Job Evaluation and Grading Support) for non-SCS staff and JESP (Job Evaluation for Senior Posts) for SCS staff. These have been developed specifically for the Civil Service. It is a systematic process for defining the relative worth or size of jobs in order to establish internal relativities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The procedure for assessing grade boundaries using job evaluation are:</p><p> </p><p>1. Form a clear picture of the job</p><p> </p><p>2. Refer to grading guidance and where possible allocate to a grade</p><p> </p><p>3. If not, a trained evaluator will evaluate the post</p><p> </p><p>4. The evaluator’s conclusions are quality assured by an appropriate panel which includes trade union representatives</p><p> </p><p>5. HR will communicate the outcome to the line manager</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We do not keep records of how often the grading guidance are used or when job evaluations have taken place. Possible reasons for formal job evaluation might include:</p><p> </p><p>· the recruiting manager, Independent Panel Member (IPM) and Deputy Director cannot agree on the appropriate grade using the BIS grading guidance;</p><p> </p><p>· a new post has arisen and there are limited comparator posts within which to agree the grading;</p><p> </p><p>· a substantial and material change has been made to the weighting and responsibilities of the post;</p><p> </p><p>· an area has been restructured and the boundaries for responsibility and weighting have changed significantly;</p><p> </p><p>· there is sufficient doubt of grading when similar roles are compared across the Department; or</p><p> </p><p>· the Department is undergoing a full grading review.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-30T14:58:14.8036748Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100779/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100779/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-23","Job Evaluation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the procedure is in his Department for assessing grade boundaries and job roles; and how often such assessments take place.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100780","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-04","<p>Information on students awarded and paid Disabled Students’ Allowance is published annually by Student Loans Company (SLC) ’. The latest statistics are available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/media/694170/slcsfr052013.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/media/694170/slcsfr052013.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of students who received disabled students’ allowance in each parliamentary constituency in the East Midlands in each of the last three years is provided in the table. Comparable data for earlier years is not readily available.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-11-04T16:46:20.2262067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100780/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100780/answer","Table for 211838.xlsx","Table for 211838.xlsx","Students in receipt of Disabled Students Allowance","Students in receipt of Disabled Students Allowance","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100780/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100780/answer/previousversion/24850","Biography information for Greg Clark","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-23","Disabled Students' Allowances: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many people in each parliamentary constituency in the East Midlands received disabled students' allowance in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","211838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100781","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-29","<p>After this matter was raised by the Hon. Member for Bradford South (Gerry Sutcliffe) at Prime Minister’s Questions on 28 June 2014, I, along with officials from the Insolvency Service, held a meeting with the Hon. Member for Bradford South, Mr Sutcliffe, on 17 July 2014. Mr Sutcliffe is head of the All-Party Parliamentary Group for this issue, and therefore representative of stakeholders’ views. At that meeting he handed over further information from the liquidators of two companies which operated the extended warranty schemes sold by Scottish Power, and we agreed that the Insolvency Service would review this information to ascertain whether or not further investigation was appropriate. It was explained to Mr Sutcliffe that any decision whether or not to commence an investigation using s447 Companies Act would be confidential and the Insolvency Service would not be in a position to confirm that decision or comment further.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-29T16:07:52.9974936Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100781/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100781/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-23","Scottish Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has held with stakeholders on the nature of the warranties sold by Scottish Power to its customers in the 1980s and 1990s.","false","Biography information for Mr William Bain","Glasgow North East","Mr William Bain","211767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100782","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-28","<p>Details of Ministerial overseas travel is published on a quarterly basis.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-10-28T15:09:24.1696695Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100782/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100782/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-23","Minister Without Portfolio","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many times the Minister without Portfolio has travelled overseas on an official visit since his appointment to that post; what the (a) purpose and (b) cost of each such visit was; and what the class of travel was for each journey on each such visit.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100783","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Government intends to adopt a flexible approach to defining the off site carbon abatement measures (allowable solutions) which can be supported by house builders to meet their zero carbon obligation and not apply restrictions which would rule out innovative, cost effective approaches. The Government’s consultation on “Next Steps to Zero Carbon – Allowable Solutions” set out examples of potential measures which could be supported, including renewable energy measures. The Government has not considered support for carbon capture and storage or nuclear power in the context of allowable solutions. However, the criteria based approach set out in the consultation for identifying appropriate carbon abatement measures would require that measures will need to bring forward additional, verifiable carbon savings at a cost effective price. Given carbon capture and storage, and nuclear power, would have high upfront costs, they would be unlikely to be cost-effective.</p>","Bristol West","Stephen Williams",,"2014-10-30T16:37:28.7240597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100783/answer","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100783/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-10-23","Housing: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether, in delivery of the Zero Carbon Homes policy, house builders can contract with a third party to deliver the carbon abatement measures outside of the built environment in (a) renewable energy technologies, (b) carbon capture and storage and (c) nuclear power in order to meet the house builder's zero carbon obligation.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","211768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100784","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-10-28","<p>In its consultation on the future of the 700MHz band, Ofcom highlights the important benefits that PMSE delivers to the UK. Ofcom sets out a clear objective, in case of a change of use of those frequencies away from existing services including PMSE, to continue to secure those important benefits. Its plan to achieve this includes improving the way current use takes place as well as securing access to alternative frequencies and Ofcom is working closely with stakeholders through its regular engagement with the British Entertainment Industry Radio Group.</p><p>I welcome Ofcom’s recognition of the significant value that PMSE delivers and we fully support their work on mitigating the effect of loss of access to the 700MHz band. This is an integral part of any change to the 700 MHz band and the DCMS will continue to monitor Ofcom’s work in this.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-10-28T09:38:51.9022816Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100784/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100784/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-23","Broadcasting: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 September 2014 to Question 206821, what assessment his Department has made of the risk of PMSE market failure if PMSE users are not allocated alternative spectrum in which to operate before the 799 MHz band is cleared; what discussions his Department has had with Ofcom regarding mitigating that risk; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Luff","Mid Worcestershire","Sir Peter Luff","211778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100785","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-10-28","<p>DCMS is currently working closely with HMT and Ofcom to examine all aspects of clearing the 700MHz band, including in relation to PMSE. Once a decision on the future of the 700MHz band has been made and timelines for any programme have been finalised, it will be possible to consider any compensation scheme for PMSE.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-10-28T09:39:54.7817824Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100785/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100785/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-23","Broadcasting: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 September 2014 to Question 206821, how many meetings (a) his Department and (b) Ofcom have had with HM Treasury on compensation for the Programme Making and Special Events sector if the 700 MHz band was cleared of such users; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Luff","Mid Worcestershire","Sir Peter Luff","211779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100786","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-10-28","<p>Ofcom published a statement in May on its strategy to deal with the growing demand for mobile data services.</p><p> </p><p>In that document Ofcom highlighted that there are a wide range of long term forecasts both in terms of traffic levels and set out the subsequent implications for future spectrum requirements. Ofcom will continue to review the growth in mobile data demand, and consequently how much spectrum (in addition to public sector spectrum in the 2.3 GHz and 3.4 GHz bands and the proposed release of the 700 MHz band) it might be beneficial to make available for mobile data services in the future. However, this type of analysis is inherently subject to a high degree of uncertainty, and therefore Ofcom is working to ensure there are sufficient spectrum options for the future to deal with this demand if and when it emerges.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-10-28T09:38:03.7825286Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100786/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100786/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-23","Broadcasting: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 September 2014 to Question 206823, what assessment his Department has made of the future possibility of mobile network operators demanding access to more spectrum; what steps his Department is taking to test the validity of such future demands; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Luff","Mid Worcestershire","Sir Peter Luff","211780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100787","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-10-28","<blockquote><p> </p><p>The Ministry Of Defence provides a grant of £25,000 to the hosts of an Armed Forces Day National event. The grant is a fixed amount given each year. The total cost to Guildford Borough Council will be dependent on their specific plans for this prestigious event.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p></blockquote>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-10-28T16:40:19.6466406Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100787/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100787/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Armed Forces Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the budget is for the Armed Forces Day national event in Guildford on 27 June 2015; how much of that cost is being met by (a) his Department and (b) Guildford Borough Council; whether any public funding so provided is dependent on match funding from industry or other sources; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","211802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100788","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-04","<p>I am withholding the information as its disclosure would or would be likely to prejudice operational capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces and also relations between the United Kingdom and another State.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-04T17:27:25.9100117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100788/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100788/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100788/answer/previousversion/25424","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Written Statement of 21 October 2014, Official Report, column 63WS, on the Middle East, from which bases the UK's (a) Reaper UAVs and (b) River Joint aircraft operate for their surveillance missions over Iraq and Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100789","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-04","<p>We have initially deployed two Reaper aircraft for operations in the Middle East, including for surveillance missions over Syria. As Reaper numbers in Afghanistan reduce we intend to move more to the Middle East, adding to our coverage.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-04T17:28:37.2591959Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100789/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100789/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100789/answer/previousversion/25423","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Written Statement of 21 October 2014, Official Report, column 63WS, on the Middle East, how many of the UK's Reaper aircraft will be deployed for surveillance missions over Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100790","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-10-28","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 3 March 2014, (Official Report, column 720W) to the hon. Member for Washington and Sunderland West (Mrs Hodgson).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","211775","2014-10-28T17:55:33.4140205Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100790/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100790/answer","20140303 - Hansard extract Maternity Leave.doc","20140303 - Hansard extract Maternity Leave.doc","20140303 - Hansard extract on Maternity Leave","20140303 - Hansard extract on Maternity Leave","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100790/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many nursery places his Department offers; how many applications have there been for such places in each year since 2010; and how many such places currently on offer are occupied.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100791","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-02","<p>The table shows approximately how much the Department has spent in each Financial Year since 2010 on teaching English to Service personnel. It is difficult to give exact figures as, in some cases, the cost of English tuition cannot be separated from that for other tuition areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td>Financial Year £ million</td><td>2010-11</td><td>2011-12</td><td>2012-13</td><td>2013-14</td></tr><tr><td>Expenditure</td><td>£1.637</td><td>£1.667</td><td>£1.695</td><td>£1.735</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, for those who speak English as a second language the Ministry of Defence has spent the following amounts on ‘English Speakers of Other Languages’ assessments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td>Financial Year</td><td>2010-11</td><td>2011-12</td><td>2012-13</td><td>2013-14</td></tr><tr><td>Expenditure</td><td>£13,943</td><td>£71,628</td><td>£43,159</td><td>£22,646</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","211774","2014-12-02T17:22:22.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100791/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100791/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100791/answer/previousversion/25427","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","English Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent on teaching English in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100792","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-10","<p>The number of personnel who have applied to the Joint Service Housing Advice Office referral scheme and have been housed is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of applicants*</p></td><td><p>Number housed via the scheme</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>196</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>185</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>130</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>866</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p><p>(as at 24 October)</p></td><td><p>174</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>* In 2013, a database transfer of historical data only retained those applicants who were still eligible between the years 2010-2012 at that time. Consequently figures for 2010-12 are only for eligible applicants whereas those for 2013-14 also include ineligible applicants.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-10T17:34:53.2867178Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100792/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100792/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100792/answer/previousversion/25426","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Veterans: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many personnel have been placed on his Department's referral scheme co-ordinated by the Joint Service Housing Advice Office in each year since 2010; and how many personnel so referred successfully found accommodation through the scheme in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100793","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-10-30","<p>We launched the £200 million Forces Help to Buy Scheme in April 2014 to encourage and support those Service families that aspire to home ownership. I am pleased to report that the scheme has proved very popular. As at 28 October 2014, it had received close to 5,000 applications. It has already helped over 1,500 Service personnel get on, or stay on, the property ladder.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-10-30T17:35:20.4048735Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100793/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100793/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Armed Forces: Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many applications there have been to the Armed Forces' Help to Buy scheme since it was launched in April 2014; and how many applicants to that scheme have successfully secured mortgages through the scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100794","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Government estimates that there are 4.5 million Armed Forces veterans in the United Kingdom. In the UK, veterans are defined as those who have served for at least one day in HM Armed Forces. This figure includes both former Regular and Reservist personnel.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-10-30T16:48:50.2012767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100794/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100794/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the number of veterans in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100795","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Disposal Services Authority (DSA) disposes of defence equipment that is surplus to requirement. The following table provides sales figures that accrued to the DSA for permanent Ministry of Defence bases overseas in financial year 2013-14.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Location</strong></p></td><td><p>Sales £(thousands)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Belize</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cyprus (Sovereign Base Area)</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>1,286</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gibraltar</p></td><td><p>234</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kenya</p></td><td><p>537</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nepal</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sierra Leone</p></td><td><p>146</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Details on individual sales could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-10-30T17:30:27.5921203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100795/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100795/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what income has accrued to his Department from the sale of surplus defence equipment in countries with Ministry of Defence bases; and what the details are of each such sale.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100796","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Department uses different management information systems to record its recruitment of civilians and Service personnel. The requested information has, therefore, been provided in two separate tables attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-11T17:25:39.0244518Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100796/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100796/answer","211796 - Recruitment of Civilian and Service Personnel Enginners.doc","211796 - Recruitment of Civilian and Service Personnel Enginners.doc","MOD Civillian and Service Personnel Engineers","MOD Civillian and Service Personnel Engineers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100796/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100796/answer/previousversion/25425","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-23","Engineers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many engineers have been recruited by his Department in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100797","Department for Education","false","2014-10-30","<p>The numbers of service children recorded in schools in England since 2010 are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of Service Children [1] [2]</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>53,850</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>50,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>49,750</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>48,070</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>38,110</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department for Education is responsible for education in England only and not the whole of the United Kingdom. Information on the devolved administrations; Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales is available via their websites.[3]</p><p> </p><p>[1] Data taken from the National Pupil Database, Spring Census data, 2010-2014</p><p>[2] Figures are rounded to the nearest ten</p><p>[3] Northern Ireland: <a href="http://www.deni.gov.uk/index/facts-and-figures-new/education-statistics.htm" target="_blank">www.deni.gov.uk/index/facts-and-figures-new/education-statistics.htm</a></p><p>Scotland: <a href="http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Statistics/Browse/School-Education" target="_blank">www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Statistics/Browse/School-Education</a></p><p>Wales: <a href="http://www.wales.gov.uk/topics/statistics/?lang=en" target="_blank">www.wales.gov.uk/topics/statistics/?lang=en</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-10-30T15:33:14.2293437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100797/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100797/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-10-23","Armed Forces: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many service children have been recorded in the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100798","Department for Education","false","2014-10-28","<p>The School Admissions Code 2012 requires all state-funded schools to give admission priority to looked-after and previously looked-after children. [1]</p><p>In May this year the Department issued additional guidance to clarify its position for school admission authorities in relation to children adopted from local authority care. This was to ensure that all children adopted from local authority care in England and Wales should have the highest priority rather than restricting priority to those children adopted from care under the Adoption and Children Act 2002.</p><p>The most recent report of the Office of the Schools Adjudicator indicates that this requirement has been met in most of the arrangements seen by adjudicators (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/307182/osa_annual_report_12-13.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/307182/osa_annual_report_12-13.pdf</a>) but acknowledges there is more to be done to ensure that all schools comply fully with this requirement.</p><p>The Children and Families Act 2014 included a new provision to place the role of Virtual School Head (VSH) on a statutory footing. VSHs have a role in promoting the education of the children their authority looks after and that includes ensuring everyone understands the requirements in the Code.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Previously looked-after children are those who have been adopted from care and those who left care under a Special Guardianship Order or Residence (now Child Arrangements) Order.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-10-28T17:41:31.1748743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100798/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100798/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-10-23","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 21 October 2014 from the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Schools to the Earl of Listowel, Official Report, House of Lords, column 553, what estimate she has made of the number of schools that do not prioritise looked-after children.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","211783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100799","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-30","<p>The response relates to formal personal improvement plans under DECC poor performance policy. The response to your question is in the table below, and the figures are out of 1579 civil servants working in DECC:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>(a) are currently on a personal improvement plan</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(b) have been on a personal improvement plan for over one year</p></td><td><p>None</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(c) have been on a personal improvement plan for more than two consecutive years</p></td><td><p>None</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In relation to (a), the grades of such staff are: Grade 6, Grade 7, Higher Executive Officer (HEO) and Executive Officer (EO).</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-10-30T15:11:09.0939361Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100799/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100799/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-23","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many staff in his Department (a) are currently on a persoanl improvement plan, (b) have been on a personal improvement plan for over one year and (c) have been on a personal improvement plan for more than two consecutive years; and what the grades are or were of such staff.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100800","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-29","<p>All individuals on personal improvement plans are supported and coached by their line manager.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-10-29T14:35:01.9960709Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100800/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100800/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-23","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many staff in his Department are responsible for mentoring staff on personal improvement plans.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100801","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-29","<p>Grades across the Civil Service are defined by job weight, which is a measure of a job’s complexity and responsibilities. Job weight in the Department of Energy and Climate Change is determined by a job evaluation system called JESP (Job Evaluation for Senior Posts) for the senior Civil Service (SCS) and JEGS (Job Evaluation &amp; Grading Support) at grades below SCS.</p><p>A formal JESP evaluation should be undertaken where:</p><p>· a new post is created and the pay band is not obvious</p><p>· an existing post changes significantly, raising doubt about the pay band</p><p>· posts are on the boundary of different pay bands</p><p>· posts are subject to a grading review</p><ul><li>a pay banding decision is disputed.</li></ul><p>DECC has not undertaken any formal JESP assessments in the past 12 months.</p><p>Grade boundaries and job roles for staff below the SCS are initially assessed by reference to the Department’s grading guidance. Before advertising a new or existing post the recruiting manager should assess the grade of a post using the guidance. Any changes to the grade of a job role must be authorised in local business area by senior managers.</p><p>JEGS is only formally used when the appropriate grade cannot be clearly determined by reference to the grading guidance. In most cases, roles will fall readily into a grade on this basis.</p><p>No central records are held of local grading assessments. One formal JEGS assessment has been carried out within the last 12 months.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-10-29T14:33:49.976799Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100801/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100801/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-23","Job Evaluation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the procedure is in his Department for assessing grade boundaries and job roles; and how often such assessments take place.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100802","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-30","<p>DECC has defined team as a directorate for the purpose of this response. Currently there are 2 directorates that have more than one member of staff on a personal improvement plan. The response relates to formal personal improvement plans under DECC poor performance policy.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-10-30T15:13:48.8412998Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100802/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100802/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-23","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many teams in his Department have more than one member of staff on personal improvement plans.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100803","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-30","<p>Following the closure of the language centre under the previous Government, the former Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right Hon. Friend the Member for Richmond (Yorks.) (Mr Hague), restablished one in 2013. Fulltime language training (FTLT) is provided for all officers going overseas where the ability to communicate effectively in another language is considered essential to meet the requirements of their role. Training is provided to either C1 operational level or C2 Extensive level depending on the job requirements. The FCO also provides language training to A2 Confidence level to staff and their spouses/partners being posted overseas into non speaker roles. In 2012 the FCO also introduced a developmental language training programme to enable all staff to learn a new language or maintain existing language skills. The table below summarises the annual spend on all three language training programmes since 2010. Essential fulltime language training includes a period of training overseas. Research has shown that the experience of immersing themselves in a new language and culture makes a huge difference to students’ learning and their future effectiveness in their job. The associated costs of immersion are shown in Row B. Financial Year 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014 2015 (forecast) A: Language Training costs only 2,034,609 2,231,436 2,350,730 2,999,781 3,223,107 3,242,509 B: Associated costs (e.g. travel, accommodation etc) 418,964 772,472 626,807 385,895 682,257 782,720 C: Total spend 2,453,573 3,003,908 2,977,537 3,385,676 3,905,364 4,025,229</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-30T14:48:35.3935418Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100803/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100803/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-23","Languages: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on language training in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100804","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-12-17","<p>The FCO has spent the following amounts with PSC (Private Security Companies) year by year since 2010: 2010/2011:2011/2012:2012/2013:2013/2014 G4S: £28,916,168 :£30,081,113:£31,391,478:£35,285,387 Control Risks Group: £453,477:£5,573,212:£920,281:£1,208,369 Aegis: £4,211:£183,516:£563,184:£556,920 Minimal Risk :£1,951,611:£1,744,356:£2,122,113:£1,707,150 Gardaworld :£17,291,485:£16,381,944:£17,498,010:£,342,201 PSCs are contracted in a number of countries to carry out a variety of activities and duties including the static protection of premises and the close protection of personnel. They play a vital and necessary protective role in hostile environments, and enable the Government and partner organisations to carry out their work by providing essential security services.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-12-17T13:56:24.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100804/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100804/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-23","Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on private security companies in each year since 2010; and what the contractual arrangements were with each such company.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100805","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office provides a wide range of security courses. Most are conducted in-house. A three-day Security Awareness in Fragile Environments (SAFE) residential training course, with an additional one-day SAFE+ Close Protection module, is provided by an external contractor.</p><p>Costs for all security and hostile environment training were as follows:</p><p>2010/11 : £414,028.32<br>2011/12 : £500,164.52<br>2012/13 : £484,826.55<br>2013/14 : £535,437.82</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-29T15:52:55.1995409Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100805/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100805/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-23","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on security and hostile environment training in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100806","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>We expect any State wishing to transport detainees via UK territory, including our Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies, to seek permission to do so. The Government will grant that permission only if satisfied that such transportation would be in accordance with UK law and our international obligations. Detained persons should remain within the protection of the law at all times.</p><p>Government policy on the principles governing the detention and interviewing of detainees overseas, and on the passing and receipt of intelligence relating to detainees, is set out in the Consolidated Guidance published in July 2010. The Consolidated Guidance is consistent with UK domestic law and international law obligations, and requires an assessment of the standards to which the detainee may have been/or may be subject.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-10-29T16:25:44.1427295Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100806/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100806/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-23","Rendition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is on (a) the transportation of detainees held by another state through UK territory, including UK colonies and dependent territories, other than pursuant to a lawful extradition proceeding, (b) attendance of UK agents at interrogations of detainees by or on behalf of a foreign state and (c) supplying questions for use in interrogating detainees held by foreign states.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","211801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100807","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>The following table shows spend figures, by the Department and Public Health England, for public awareness campaigns on cancer between 2010-11 and 2013-14:</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Media Spend (£ millions)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>0.55</p></td><td><p>3.76</p></td><td><p>6.46</p></td><td><p>7.38</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><p>1. Since 2010-11 the Department has run a serioes of <em>Be Clear on Cancer</em> campagins, in April 2013 reponsibility for these campagins transfrered to Public Health England.</p><p> </p><p>2. Figures are net plus media buying agency fees and commissions (rounded to nearest £10,000)</p><p> </p><p>3. Figures exclude VAT and Central Office of Information (COI) fees.</p><p> </p><p>4. Media spend includes expenditure for advertising on Television, Radio, National Press, Regional Press, Out of Home (Outdoor), Cinema and Digital.</p><p> </p><p>5. Final figures for 2014-15 are not yet available.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-28T16:55:22.1351461Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100807/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100807/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department has spent on public awareness campaigns on cancer in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","211804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100808","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>This is an independent report, a publication date has not been agreed, however we expect it to be shortly.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-28T14:34:43.0382082Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100808/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100808/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","Alcoholic Drinks: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2014 to Question 210930, when the final independent market survey will report.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","211834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100809","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>The Chief Medical Officer wrote to National Health Service medical and nursing directors on 19 September seeking volunteers to help efforts on the ground in West Africa. Currently 886 NHS staff have put their names forward. Not all of them will be accepted and NHS trusts will have to agree to their staff taking special leave. Funding for backfilling these posts will be available to NHS trusts.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Additionally, a number of NHS staff are working as volunteers to tackle Ebola in West Africa. This is primarily done on an individual basis through voluntary and non-Government organisations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department, with NHS England and others, will ensure that the NHS remains resilient going forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-28T16:13:32.0252732Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100809/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100809/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","Ebola: West Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many NHS staff are helping with Ebola in West Africa; and what steps he has taken to provide cover for those staff.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","211805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100810","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>Information about the number of iPads and iPhones procured by the Department and the Department’s non-departmental public bodies is available in the attached table, broken down by financial years.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-10-28T17:48:50.4618488Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100810/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100810/answer","ipad and iphone Procurement Department of Health.docx","ipad and iphone Procurement Department of Health.docx","iPhone & iPad Procurement Dept of Health","iPhone & iPad Procurement Dept of Health","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100810/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much (a) his Department, (b) Public Health England, (c) NHS England and (d) each non-departmental public body spent on (i) iPads and (ii)iPhones in each of the last five years; and how many of each were purchased in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","211806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100811","Department of Health","false","2014-10-30","<p>Through the World Health Organization Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (WHO FCTC), 179 countries have agreed to work together to reduce smoking rates, to prevent the uptake by children and to minimise the burden that tobacco use has on health. The United Kingdom remains an active participant in the WHO FCTC, as we have been since it began.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK attended the WHO FCTC to work with other countries to agree further on how this can be achieved around the world.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","211811","2014-10-30T17:17:10.7729308Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100811/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100811/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations his Department made to international counterparts during the conference of the parties to the World Health Organisation Framework Convention on Tobacco Control in Moscow.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","211810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100812","Department of Health","false","2014-10-30","<p>Through the World Health Organization Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (WHO FCTC), 179 countries have agreed to work together to reduce smoking rates, to prevent the uptake by children and to minimise the burden that tobacco use has on health. The United Kingdom remains an active participant in the WHO FCTC, as we have been since it began.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK attended the WHO FCTC to work with other countries to agree further on how this can be achieved around the world.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","211810","2014-10-30T17:17:11.0017352Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100812/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100812/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reason his Department attended the conference of the parties to the World Health Organisation Framework Convention on Tobacco Control in Moscow.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","211811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100813","Department of Health","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Department received no such representations.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-30T16:50:19.8616501Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100813/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100813/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations his Department received urging them to boycott the conference of the parties to the World Health Organisation Framework Convention on Tobacco Control.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","211812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100814","Department of Health","false","2014-10-30","<p>The sixth Conference of the Parties (COP) of the World Health Organization Framework Convention on Tobacco Control was held in Moscow over 13-18 October 2014. To be able to participate in the full range of business at the COP, the United Kingdom was represented by two officials.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The United Kingdom’s delegation travelled on economy class flights to Moscow and stayed during the COP in the hotel where the conference was held, however total costs are not yet available.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-10-30T16:55:06.8450243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100814/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100814/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department spent on attendance at the conference of the parties to the World Health Organisation Framework Convention on Tobacco Control in Moscow; and whose travel, accommodation and other expenses related to attendance at the conference his Department paid for.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","211813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100815","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>The Government is working to improve perinatal mental health services, collaborating closely with partner organisations including NHS England, Health Education England and the Institute of Health Visiting.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Specialised Perinatal Mental Health Services (Mother and Baby Units) are a part of a wider network of services that provide care for this patient group and the commissioning of the ‘specialist’ (local) and ‘specialised’ (national) pathway is a responsibility shared between NHS England, clinical commissioning groups and local authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Health Education England is working with partners to ensure that pre and post registration training in perinatal mental health is available to enable specialist staff to be available to every birthing unit by 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has funded the Institute of Health Visitors to train a network of 375 perinatal mental health visitor champions. This training initiative addresses the requirements that are necessary for health visitors to manage anxiety, mild to moderate depression and other perinatal mental disorders and to understand the impact of these disorders on the child, the family and society, and to know when to refer on.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England will, through its Maternity and Children Strategic Clinical Networks support the continued development of maternity and perinatal mental health networks to drive improvements to access, quality of care and inter-service communication that enhances the experience of women and families generally, and more specifically for the large numbers of women who are at risk of poor mental health during pregnancy and following childbirth.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-10-28T14:52:39.5730094Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100815/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100815/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the oral Answer of 21 October 2014 from the Minister of State for Care and Support, Official Report, column 749, on mental health nurses, what significant improvements to perinatal mental services have been made.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","211840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100816","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>The Department has not issued any such guidance. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence is an independent body and is responsible for the development of its methods and processes.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-10-28T14:56:20.6436753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100816/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100816/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department has issued to health technology appraisal committees on application of NICE's end of life criteria when appraising treatments for patients with terminal illness.","false","Biography information for Ian Swales","Redcar","Ian Swales","211809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100817","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>In January 2009, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) issued supplementary advice to its appraisal committees on appraising treatments which may be life-extending for patients, with short life expectancy, and which are licensed for indications affecting small numbers of patients with incurable illnesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This sets out the following three criteria that must all be satisfied for this supplementary advice to be applied:</p><p> </p><p>- the treatment is indicated for patients with a short life expectancy, normally less than 24 months;</p><p> </p><p>- there is sufficient evidence to indicate that the treatment offers an extension to life, normally of at least an additional three months, compared to current NHS treatment; and</p><p> </p><p>- the treatment is licensed or otherwise indicated, for small patient populations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These criteria were developed following public consultation and set out the circumstances when NICE considers it is appropriate for its appraisal committees to apply greater flexibility in their appraisal of these treatments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The advice has now been incorporated chapter 6 of <em>Guide to the methods of technology appraisal 2013 </em>which can be found at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/article/pmg9/chapter/6-the-appraisal-of-the-evidence-and-structured-decision-making" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/article/pmg9/chapter/6-the-appraisal-of-the-evidence-and-structured-decision-making</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-10-28T14:27:08.2752956Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100817/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100817/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-23","Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what rationale lies behind NICE's advice that end-of-life criteria should only apply to medicines that extend life by at least three months.","false","Biography information for Ian Swales","Redcar","Ian Swales","211807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100818","Home Office","false","2014-10-28","<p>All providers are required under the COMPASS contracts to provide a minimum level of support to asylum seekers accommodated in their properties, this includes briefing the service user in a language that they understand, on how to contact the provider and the Home Office to make complaints.<br><br>G4S does make a record of all telephone calls they receive from asylum applicants accommodated in their property and refers service users to their interpreters where it is clear that an interpreter is required.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-10-28T14:19:40.8106604Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100818/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100818/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-23","G4S","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether G4S records (a) telephone calls made to it by asylum seekers who have ended the call as they have not been able to explain that they need an interpreter and (b) all other telephone calls received in connection with its contract to deliver accommodation for asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Ian Swales","Redcar","Ian Swales","211808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100819","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-28","<p>I spoke to the President of Ghana and others in Government when I visited Ghana earlier this year about furthering economic development in the country. Those discussions included how we could help to foster growth in the agricultural sector in ways that will benefit poor farmers. I visited sites where DFID is supporting initiatives to do this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In Ghana, DFID has three projects whose primary aim is to enable poor farmers to earn more income. One is centred on two irrigation schemes that will benefit thousands of small-scale farmers. Another is an investment fund to help agricultural businesses. The third provides support to improve the way that markets work for poor people, concentrating on six agricultural products. DFID aims to ensure that 30,000 poor producers in Ghana have improved access to services by March 2016.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-10-28T16:31:15.8618868Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100819/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100819/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-23","Ghana","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her Ghanaian counterparts on the use of UK aid to support small-scale farmers in that country.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","211766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100820","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-29","<p>Detail on fraud broken down on a country by country basis is contained within DFID’s Annual Report for 2013/14.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-10-29T17:21:28.5997395Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100820/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100820/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-23","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many (a) open and (b) closed cases are listed on her Department's fraud register; and to which countries each such case relates.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100821","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-29","<p>DFID centrally contracted language training providers in 2012.</p><p> </p><p>Spend for each year since then is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£7,523.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£17,977</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£20,586.96</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Collating spend figures for prior years would incur disproportionate costs as training would have been procured locally.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-10-29T17:47:02.4516164Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100821/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100821/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-23","Languages: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department spent on language training in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100822","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-29","<p>DFID provides Security Awareness in Fragile Environments training for staff working in these locations. Spend for each year has been:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£137,054.18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£371,236.90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£305,195.24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£191,138.37</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Expenditure for 2010 is not available as this was prior to a central contract being awarded.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-10-29T17:48:22.4383625Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100822/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100822/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-23","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department spent on security and hostile environment  training in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100823","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-28","<p>Each magistrate in England and Wales is assigned to a local justice area. I have therefore interpreted the reference to ‘local authority area’ in the question to mean local justice area.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 provides the number of magistrates in each local justice area along with their gender and ethnic breakdown.</p><p> </p><p>The number of magistrates recruited in each local justice area is dictated by the business needs of the magistrates’ courts. Due in part to falling crime levels, the workload of the magistrates’ court has reduced in recent years. Table 2 provides the number of magistrates recruited in each local justice area in the last five years.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-28T15:17:56.8291487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100823/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100823/answer","Table 1 - 211837 - Number of magistrates.xls ; Table 2 - 211837 - Number of magistrates.xls","Table 1 - 211837 - Number of magistrates.xls ; Table 2 - 211837 - Number of magistrates.xls","Table 1 ; Table 2","Table 1 ; Table 2","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100823/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-23","Magistrates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many magistrates there are in each local authority area; what the gender and ethnic composition is of magistrates in each such area; and what recruitment of magistrates there has been in each such area in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","211837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100824","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-28","<p>Good progress has been made on introducing flexible ticketing. The Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern (TSGN) rail franchise includes an obligation to introduce carnet-based season tickets on smartcards by 30 September 2015. The Essex Thameside franchise includes a similar obligation to introduce flexible season tickets and carnets. We plan to trial flexible ticketing through a combination of research and analysis, as well as evaluation of data from these flexible ticketing schemes. Conclusions around price, flexibility, the impacts on operator revenue and other ticket prices will be central to any decisions on wider roll-out.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-28T15:51:31.550177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100824/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100824/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-23","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress he has made on his Department's plan in Rail Fares and Ticketing published in October 2013 to trial flexible ticketing; when he expects flexible ticketing to be rolled out and available across the whole rail network; what recent representations he has received from train operating companies on such tickets; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","211803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100825","Women and Equalities","false","2014-10-28","<p>The Government Equalities Office made the following public appointments to the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) in each of the last five years:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female*</p><p> </p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>* includes two reappointments</p><p>The EHRC Chair and Deputy Chair posts are salaried and the salaries over the period are shown below. The significant reduction in the remuneration is a result of the reduction in terms and conditions following the Government’s comprehensive review of the EHRC:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chair (male)</p></td><td><p>£124,000</p></td><td><p>£124,000</p></td><td><p>£147,000</p></td><td><p>£65,000</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chair (female)</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£55,838</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Deputy Chair (both female)</p></td><td><p>£59,533</p></td><td><p>£65,800</p></td><td><p>£65,800</p></td><td><p>£85,000 (including period as interim Chair)</p></td><td><p>£23,400</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Commissioners receive £400 a day plus expenses. In addition, two male Disability Commissioners were required to carry out additional work during the period, therefore additional payments were made as shown:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chair of the Inquiry into disability related harassment</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£8,875</p></td><td><p>£11,750</p></td><td><p>£2,375</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lead on Disability Committee Review</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£18,800</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The total of fees and expenses paid each year to each Commissioner is available in the relevant EHRC annual report and accounts.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-28T09:02:42.0148887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100825/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100825/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2014-10-23","Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Ministers for Women and Equalities, how many (a) men and (b) women her Department has publicly appointed in each of the last five years; and how much has been paid to each (i) man and (ii) woman.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","211836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100826","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p>DWP uses two job evaluation schemes, which are widely utilised across the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>1. Job Evaluation and Grading Support (JEGS), an analytical points-based system which is used by trained evaluators to rank roles from AA to Grade 6. This also incorporates Grading Guidance which provides an analytical matching of posts based on JEGS, a good level of assurance and is less resource intensive than a full evaluation.</p><p> </p><p>2. Job Evaluation for Senior Posts (JESP) which is similar to JEGS but used to evaluate posts in the Senior Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DWP evaluates all new roles and roles where there has been a fundamental or material change in job content using one of these schemes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on JEGS, including use of grading guidance, is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/job-evaluation-and-grading-support-jegs-for-civil-servants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/job-evaluation-and-grading-support-jegs-for-civil-servants</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on JESP is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/job-evaluation-for-senior-posts-good-practice-guide" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/job-evaluation-for-senior-posts-good-practice-guide</a></p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-10-28T14:19:49.2906383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100826/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100826/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-23","Job Evaluation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the procedure is in his Department for assessing grade boundaries and job roles; and how often such assessments take place.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","211827"
