"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100836","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p /> <p>The data requested is not available. Motability is wholly responsible for the administration of the Motability scheme including collating its own management information. Questions about the number of vehicles returned because claimants are not entitled to the enhanced rate of the mobility component of personal independence payment (PIP) can be sent to: Declan O’Mahony, Director, Motability, Warwick House, Roydon Road, Harlow, Essex, CM195PX.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-28T11:41:59.8913268Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100836/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100836/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-23","Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of former disability living allowance claimants who use a Motability vehicle have had the vehicle removed after being moved to personal independence payment; and what savings have accrued to the Exchequer as a result.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","211782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100290","Attorney General","false","2014-10-28","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) has developed two online e-Learning courses on all types of stalking. The “Cyber Crime: Cyber Stalking” course includes cyber stalking, non-cyber stalking and harassment. The “Stalking and Harassment” course (which was released in April 2014) deals specifically with stalking and harassment offences.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CPS maintains a central record of the number of employees who have been trained on the law on stalking by way of the e-Learning courses. 1581 of its employees in post on 23 October 2014 have completed all elements of either of the e-Learning courses in the period between 1 November 2012 (the month when the Cyber Stalking e-Learning module was revised to include the new stalking offences) and 23 October 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In October 2014 the CPS issued follow-up, face-to-face training material on the Stalking and Harassment offences. It can be used flexibly at a local CPS level; accordingly, its delivery is not recorded on a central database.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Although there are no current plans for new training products to be launched, the CPS will continue to train its staff in this critical area of work.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"2014-10-28T13:15:18.0854691Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100290/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100290/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-22","Stalking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many employees of the Crown Prosecution Service have been trained on the law on stalking to date; and what further such training is planned.","true","Biography information for Ms Nadine Dorries","Mid Bedfordshire","Nadine Dorries","211538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100291","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-03","<p>The Government takes the enforcement of the National Minimum Wage (NMW) very seriously. HMRC review every complaint that is referred to them by the Pay and Work Rights Helpline. In addition, HMRC undertake targeted enforcement on employers across the United Kingdom who are more likely to be not paying NMW.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has increased the financial penalty percentage from 50% to 100% of the unpaid wages owed to workers, and the maximum penalty from £5,000 to £20,000. These new limits are now in force where arrears are identified in pay reference periods on or after 7 March 2014. The Government will also bring in primary legislation as soon as possible so that the maximum £20,000 penalty can apply to each underpaid worker.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The majority of employers identified as paying below the NMW pay arrears on receipt of a formal Notice of Underpayment. Where they do not do so, HMRC pursues recovery through the civil courts. HMRC‘s approach to tackling underpayment of NMW through the civil courts is the best way to ensure that money is paid back to the person underpaid and provides the most effective resolution for tax-payers. Criminal investigations may not result in arrears being paid to workers and are therefore reserved for the most serious cases.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-11-03T15:32:50.2694548Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100291/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100291/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-22","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2014 to Question 209683 to the hon. Member for Stourbridge, what assessment he has made of the factors that resulted in there being no prosecutions for not paying the national minimum wage in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","211604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100292","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-30","<p>The Government invited interested parties to submit evidence as part of its programme of consultation during the summer.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-10-30T15:49:22.4523441Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100292/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100292/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-22","Disabled Students' Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when the deadline was for submitting evidence for the equality analysis of proposed changes to disabled student's allowance; and how awareness of that deadline was disseminated.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","211562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100293","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-28","<p>UK Government Departments promote and support foreign direct investment, and the jobs that it can bring or safeguard, on an equal basis in all regions of the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For inward investment, UK Trade &amp; Investment (UKTI) teams are structured to support the overall strategy of promoting the “UK First”, putting forward the areas of the UK best able to meet the requirements of the particular investor and so most likely to attract that inward investment. UKTI and its national, local and overseas partners develop inward investment opportunities that meet the sector requirements of investors.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>UKTI has agreed Memoranda of Understanding with the Devolved Administrations of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland (and with Local Enterprise Partnerships and London and Partners in England) to ensure an open and equitable approach. The UKTI operating model combines strong levels of local engagement within a national framework of support, to best support inward investment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-28T16:00:51.8859807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100293/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100293/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100293/answer/previousversion/24556","Biography information for Matt Hancock","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-22","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to ensure that inward investment and job creation is encouraged on an equal basis in all the regions of the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","211579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100294","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-29","<p>In total more than 21,000 Start Up Loans have been issued to budding entrepreneurs across the country since the scheme launched in June 2012. 38 loans have been issued in Pendle constituency out of 794 loans in total across Lancashire.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-29T14:54:01.3755026Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100294/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100294/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-22","New Businesses: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many start-up loans have been granted to businesses in (a) Pendle constituency and (b) Lancashire to date.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","211613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100295","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-28","<p>The metals sector is expected to publish its strategy in Spring 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are supporting the metals sector, through the Metals Forum (an umbrella body bringing together the metals related trade associations) on the development of this strategy: this will bring metals into line with other important foundation sectors which have published strategies already. Foundation sectors are those such as metals, electronics and chemicals which underpin manufacturing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The strategy will cover issues such as sustainability, supply chains, technology &amp; innovation, skills and communication – which will all have an impact on the metals industry, including steel.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-10-28T15:57:30.0116052Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100295/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100295/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100295/answer/previousversion/24554","Biography information for Matt Hancock","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-22","Metals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Urgent Question on 16 October 2014, Official Report, column 445, on Tata Steel, when he plans to publish his Department's metals strategy.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","211585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100296","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-05","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills and officials maintain a regular dialogue with the senior management of Tata Steel.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Most recently the Secretary of State had a telephone conversation with Karl Kohler, CEO Tata Steel Europe on 29 September 2014; and met Cyrus Mistry, Chairman Tata Group in India on 14 October 2014. Official level contact is regular and ongoing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We stand ready to engage with the trades unions to discuss and listen to their views on the proposed sale.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-05T15:56:55.6262503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100296/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100296/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100296/answer/previousversion/24552","Biography information for Matt Hancock","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-22","Tata Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Urgent Question on 16 October 2014, Official Report, column 445, on Tata Steel, what meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers in his Department have held with (a) Tata Steel and (b) trades unions to discuss the selling of the Long Products Division.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","211586"
